Netflix and the NFL
-------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/media/netflix-n=
fl-christmas-games-2024-broadcast-deb9fe0b ) :

Netflix will stream at least one NFL game globally on Christmas Day for the=
 next three years, the streaming giant announced Wednesday, marking the com=
pany=E2=80=99s biggest bet on live sports yet. As part of the three-year de=
al, Netflix will broadcast the National Football League=E2=80=99s two Chris=
tmas games this year, and then will air at least one holiday game in 2025 a=
nd 2026. This year=E2=80=99s Christmas Day double-header will begin with a =
matchup between the Kansas City Chiefs and Pittsburgh Steelers, followed by=
 a game between the Baltimore Ravens and Houston Texans, the league said. N=
etflix is paying about $75 million a game this year, according to people fa=
miliar with the matter.

For Netflix, the move to stream NFL games is the latest example of the stre=
aming company experimenting with live sports without committing to multibil=
lion-dollar, multiyear sports-rights deals. Netflix executives have publicl=
y stated the company doesn=E2=80=99t want to get into bidding wars for such=
 deals.

It is a testament to how much Netflix has evolved over the last few years t=
hat, while one might have been shocked by this news five or so years ago, t=
oday it feels like a natural next step for the company.

Start with what this deal is, and isn=E2=80=99t. First, the NFL is by far t=
he biggest show in town; from Sportico ( https://www.sportico.com/business/=
media/2024/nfl-posts-93-of-top-100-tv-broadcasts-2023-1234761753/ ) in Janu=
ary:

2023 was the year the NFL swallowed our collective frame of reference. Per =
Nielsen, the league accounted for 93 of the year=E2=80=99s 100 most-watched=
 TV broadcasts, an improvement on 2022=E2=80=99s already impressive tally (=
82) and a huge leap forward compared to the 61 slots the NFL commandeered j=
ust five years ago. If it=E2=80=99s widely accepted that TV is now merely a=
 delivery system for live sports and insurance commercials, last year=E2=80=
=99s deliveries suggest that the rest of the so-called Big Four leagues hav=
e been remanded to a shadow tier.

( https://www.sportico.com/business/media/2024/nfl-posts-93-of-top-100-tv-b=
roadcasts-2023-1234761753/ )

This is a property that is obviously useful for both customer acquisition a=
nd churn mitigation; it=E2=80=99s more valuable for the former, though. Cus=
tomer acquisition is more difficult and more expensive than churn mitigatio=
n; you are trying to provoke an affirmative choice to sign-up for a service=
 (because the status quo is to not be subscribed), instead of preventing an=
 affirmative choice to cancel (because the status quo is to auto-renew). At=
 the same time, customer acquisition is something that happens once; churn =
mitigation is an ongoing effort. That, by extension, means an event with ma=
jor FOMO is better for the former, while the latter requires a large librar=
y to keep a user satisfied. And, speaking of FOMO, social media is particul=
arly useful to the extent it can generate exactly that, which requires ever=
yone to be watching something at the same time, which means something that =
is live; no one, meanwhile, wants to tweet about filler TV that is just nic=
e to have on in the background.

The problem with the NFL, though, at least from Netflix=E2=80=99s perspecti=
ve, is that it has previously only been available in a package that provide=
d both customer acquisition and churn mitigation. CBS, NBC, Fox, and ESPN s=
igned rights deals that gave them games every week, and Amazon did the same=
 for Thursday night football; Netflix, however, is doing a pretty good job,=
 particularly amongst the streamers, of holding onto its subscribers.

What the company wants to do is acquire customers, specifically for its ad-=
supported tier. There are approximately 125 million TV homes in the U.S., a=
nd Netflix is up to 81 million members in the United States and Canada afte=
r its successful password crackdown ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/featur=
es/2024-05-18/netflix-password-sharing-crackdown-was-the-start-of-nflx-come=
back ). Netflix not only wants to figure out a way to reach the parts of th=
e market that have never been interested in streaming, but also get scale f=
or its ad network. A note on each of these:

* Streaming services are attractive to both sports leagues and advertisers =
because they reach a younger demographic that does not necessarily have cab=
le; the flip side of that reality, though, is that older viewers are less l=
ikely to have streaming. That, though, is where some amount of Netflix subs=
criber growth may be, and, as a Sharp Tech emailer noted, what better time =
is there to teach grandma and grandpa how to stream than on Christmas Day w=
hen everyone wants to watch the football game?
* As I noted in my interview last week ( https://stratechery.com/2023/an-in=
terview-with-ben-thompson-at-the-moffettnathanson-technology-media-and-tele=
com-conference/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5=
LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG=
